<TITLE> Probe worries send stocks down </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, August 13 (bdnews24.com) -- Stocks fell for a second day Monday amid worries of a regulatory probe into fake beneficiary owner accounts. Ongoing merchant bank sell-offs in investor portfolio accounts to adjust margin loans also extended losses, market analysts said. "An adjustment of margin loans by merchant banks and anxiety over a Securities and Exchange Commission probe into the fake beneficiary owner accounts has affected the market. Investors with fake BO accounts are selling out shares," a senior official with the Investment Corporation of Bangladesh, an investment bank, said. The index dipped at the beginning, but regained nearly 1.0 percent until midday. It however lost pace in the second session due to sale-pressure. All three top shares in market capitalisation- Square Pharma, Lafarge Surma and Power Grid Company of Bangladesh finished down due to sell-offs. Square lost 2.0 percent to Tk 4790. Lafarge Surma ended at Tk 384, down by 1.72 percent. Power Grid dipped 1.64 percent to Tk 524. The DGEN or general index shed 14.79 points or 0.65 percent to 2239.76. The DSI or all-share price index declined 10.60 points or 0.56 percent to 1859.51. The DSE-20 blue chip index fell 13.83 points or 0.69 percent to 1987.59. Of the issues traded on the DSE, 61 gained, 134 lost and 20 remained unchanged. Turnover declined to Tk 1.05 billion from Sunday's Tk 1.09 billion. "It's a continuation of realignment phase. But there are concerns about the support level of the market," said Yawer Sayeed, who helps manage about Tk 750 million funds at AIMS of Bangladesh. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished lower. Turnover rose to Tk 123.07 million from Tk 111.81 million. Losers ruled gainers 71 to 23. Some four shares finished unchanged. On the DSE, Summit Power, the most-traded issue, added 2.47 percent to Tk 1304.5 after it declared four right shares for every five existing shares at Tk 145 each with a premium of Tk 45 for each share. Banking stocks, depressed by a fall in market heavyweights, in Rupali, Prime and Pubali Bank, finished downbeat. BRAC Bank, the most traded scrip among banks, lost 0.91 percent to Tk 890.75. Pubali Bank fell 1.55 percent to Tk 841. Profit taking pushed UCBL 2.02 percent down to Tk 3445.25. bd
